# Supersize-Solana: ER Architecture Excavation & Solracer Adaptation

> Source: https://github.com/Lewarn00/supersize-solana/tree/main  
> Framework: MagicBlock BOLT (Ephemeral Rollups on Solana)  
> Engine: No game engine. React + HTML5 Canvas. Custom game loop.

---

## SECTION 1 — Full System Architecture

### Textual Architecture Diagram

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                          CLIENT                                  │
│   React + HTML5 Canvas                                           │
│   App.tsx — monolithic game loop + state machine                 │
│     - polls ER component accounts (getAccountInfo on RPC)        │
│     - sends anchor transactions to ER endpoint (no WebSocket)    │
│     - renders local player + all remote players from ER state    │
└─────────────────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
                  │ Anchor txns (HTTP to ER RPC)
                  │ getAccountInfo polls (HTTP to ER RPC)
                  ▼
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│              MAGICBLOCK EPHEMERAL ROLLUP (bolt_lang)             │
│                                                                  │
│   Entity Component System — on-chain programs                    │
│                                                                  │
│   COMPONENTS (ECS accounts, PDAs on ER):                         │
│     Map       — game world state (delegated)                     │
│     Player    — per-player state (delegated)                     │
│     Section   — spatial food partitioning (delegated)            │
│     Anteroom  — L1 financial config (NOT delegated to ER)        │
│                                                                  │
│   SYSTEMS (deployed programs on ER):                             │
│     movement        — move player, consume mass on boost         │
│     eat-food        — player absorbs food pellets                │
│     eat-player      — collision + mass transfer between players  │
│     spawn-player    — initialise player in world                 │
│     spawn-food      — add food pellets to map section            │
│     buy-in          — verify L1 deposit, set player authority    │
│     cash-out        — verify ER state, release funds on L1       │
│     init-map        — create Map component                       │
│     init-anteroom   — create Anteroom component (L1)             │
│     init-player     — create Player component PDA                │
│     init-section    — create Section component                   │
│     exit-game       — force-remove inactive player               │
└─────────────────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
                  │ ER commits state proofs to Solana L1
                  │ on cash-out/undelegation (not tick-by-tick)
                  ▼
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                      SOLANA L1                                   │
│   - Anteroom component (vault config, token mint, buyin limits)  │
│   - SPL Token vault (holds all player buy-in funds)             │
│   - buy-in system runs on L1 (real token transfer)              │
│   - cash-out system runs on L1 (reads ER-committed player.score) │
│   - World registry (BOLT world PDA)                             │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
                  │
┌─────────────────▼────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│            LEADERBOARD BACKEND (Node.js / Prisma)                 │
│   (supersize/app/leaderboard-backend/)                            │
│   - Reads final scores from chain events off-chain               │
│   - Stores leaderboard in Postgres via Prisma                    │
│   - Purely advisory. No authority over game state.               │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

### Authority Boundaries

| Layer | Authority Over |
|---|---|
| Solana L1 | SPL token vault, anteroom config, final settlement |
| ER (BOLT) | All live game state: player positions, mass, score, food |
| Client | Input only — sends transactions to ER; no authoritative state |
| Leaderboard Backend | Advisory only — read-only score display |

### Trust Boundaries

| Component | Trusted? | Why |
|---|---|---|
| ER runtime | YES (by design) | MagicBlock ER is a trusted validator extension; programs run identically to L1 |
| Client inputs | NO | Any player can craft transactions; systems validate `authority` field |
| player.score on ER | YES at cash-out | L1 cash-out system reads from delegated Player PDA; correctness = ER program correctness |
| Leaderboard backend | NO | Advisory; can be wrong without consequence |

### State Ownership

- **ER owns**: `Player.{x, y, mass, score, speed, target_x, target_y}`, `Map.{food_queue, total_active_buyins, next_food}`, `Section.{food[]}`
- **L1 owns**: `Anteroom.{vault_token_account, token, min/max_buyin}`, actual SPL token balances
- **Client owns**: Nothing. Local render state is a visual interpolation of ER-read snapshots.

---

## SECTION 2 — Multiplayer Mechanics

### Session Creation Flow

```
1. Game owner deploys Map + Anteroom + Section components on Solana (init-map, init-anteroom, init-section)
2. Game owner creates SPL token vault owned by PDA("token_account_owner_pda", map_pubkey)
3. Player calls buy-in system on L1:
   - Transfers SPL tokens from wallet → vault
   - Sets Player.authority = player_pubkey
   - Sets Player.payout_token_account = player ATA
   - Sets Player.score = buyin_amount
4. Client delegates Player and Map components to ER via BOLT delegation instruction
5. Client calls spawn-player on ER:
   - Sets Player.x/y (xorshift64 from slot)
   - Sets Player.mass = start_mass
6. Game session is live
```

### Player Matchmaking

None. Supersize is a persistent lobby — anyone with a buy-in joins the live map immediately. No matchmaking queue. No session pairing. The Map component is the session.

### Input Capture System

- Client reads mouse position (or touch) relative to canvas center
- On each animation frame, client derives `target_x, target_y` (screen coords → world coords)
- Client sends an Anchor transaction to ER calling `movement::execute` with `{x, y, boost}`
- No batching of inputs on client — each frame is a potential transaction
- **No client-side prediction of position** — position update is the ER transaction result

### Frame/Tick System

- No fixed timestep. No server-side tick clock.
- Movement is event-driven: player sends a transaction → ER executes `movement` system → updates `Player.{x, y}`
- The ER processes transactions in its internal slot cadence (~50-400ms per transaction round-trip depending on network)
- Other players' positions are read by polling `getAccountInfo` on their Player PDA at ~100ms intervals

### Determinism Enforcement

**Partial.** The simulation is NOT globally deterministic across clients. Each client independently:
- Reads ER state (other player positions) via polling
- Renders at its own frame rate
- Sends its own movement transactions

The ER is the single authoritative state machine. Determinism is local to the ER program execution, not distributed across clients.

### State Replication Strategy

**Pull-based polling.** No WebSocket. No state diff stream. Each client calls `getAccountInfo` on relevant PDAs (Player, Map, Section) at ~100ms intervals. Receives full account data blobs. Deserializes using Borsh layout matching the component struct.

### Divergence Handling

N/A. There is no client-authoritative simulation to diverge. All state is ER-authoritative. Clients are read-only viewers of ER state. Staleness = display lag, not divergence.

### Latency Handling

- Client uses its own last-sent `{target_x, target_y}` to predict own player movement locally before ER confirmation
- Remote players rendered at last-known position (no interpolation confirmed in code)
- High latency = slow input response, no visual compensation for remote players

### Disconnect Handling

- `exit-game` system: if a player has been inactive and `scheduled_removal_time` is past, any player can call `exit-game` to force-remove them
- `Player.scheduled_removal_time` is set when player mass reaches 0

### Rejoin Behavior

Player component PDA is persistent per map. After being eaten (mass=0, score=0, authority=None), player can call `buy-in` again to rejoin without reinitialising the PDA.

---

## SECTION 3 — Ghost System

**There is no ghost system in Supersize.**

All players, including "remote" ones, are rendered identically from live ER account data. There is no ghost replay, no snapshot interpolation, no rollback, no dead reckoning.

**How a remote player appears on screen:**
```
Remote player sends movement txn to ER
  → ER updates Player.{x, y} in the delegated PDA
  → Local client polls getAccountInfo(remote_player_pda) at ~100ms
  → Client deserializes Player component
  → Client renders circle at Player.{x, y}
```

Remote players are rendered at their last polled position. No interpolation between polls. No prediction. Movement appears as discrete jumps at the poll rate.

**Implication for Solracer**: This is NOT the model you want for a racing game. Supersize is acceptable because blobs move slowly. A racing car cannot tolerate 100-400ms update intervals with no interpolation.

---

## SECTION 4 — ER Internals

### How ER Sessions Are Instantiated

MagicBlock ER uses **account delegation**. Selected Solana accounts (PDAs) are "delegated" to the ER network:
1. Owner calls `delegate` instruction on the account
2. The account is locked on L1 (writes disabled)
3. A copy is created on ER with full write access
4. ER programs (systems) can now mutate the account at ER speed

For Supersize: `Map` and [Player](file:///d:/mislanious/Unity/Uinty_projects/Solracer/backend-ts/src/types.ts#102-109) components are delegated. `Anteroom` is NOT — it stays on L1 because it holds vault config (immutable during game).

### What Data Is Stored in ER State

Each delegated account is a Borsh-serialized BOLT component struct:

```
Player: { name, authority, map, buy_in, payout_token_account,
          current_game_wallet_balance, tax, join_time, x, y, 
          target_x, target_y, score, mass, speed, 
          scheduled_removal_time, boost_click_time }

Map: { name, authority, width, height, base_buyin, max_buyin,
       min_buyin, max_players, total_active_buyins, 
       total_food_on_map, food_queue, next_food, frozen }
```

### How State Transitions Are Committed

- Each system call is an Anchor instruction submitted as a transaction to the ER RPC
- ER processes it immediately (no sequencer delay per MagicBlock docs)  
- Account data is mutated atomically per transaction
- State is committed to L1 only on **undelegation** (i.e., when cash-out is called)

### How Batching Works

No explicit batching in the client code. Each movement input is a single transaction. ER handles transaction ordering and execution at its native slot rate.

### State Serialization

Standard Borsh encoding matching Anchor account layout. Same as Solana L1. Clients use Anchor IDL to deserialize component data.

### How ER Submits to Solana

On `cash-out`:
1. Player calls cash-out system — this runs on **L1** (not ER)
2. Before it can run, the ER must have committed the Player PDA's final state back to L1 (undelegation)
3. cash-out reads `player.score` (the ER-committed value) to determine payout amount
4. Executes SPL token transfer from vault to player

### Whether ER Submits Full State, Diffs, or Commitments

Full account state is submitted on undelegation. Not diffs. Not ZK commitments. The ER is a trusted validator extension — it does not produce cryptographic proofs. It relies on the MagicBlock validator's honest execution guarantee.

### Rollback / Re-execution

Not implemented. If an ER transaction fails, the client retries. There is no client-side rollback or re-simulation.

### How ER Enforces Correctness

The BOLT framework enforces constraints inside system programs:
- `require!(player.authority == Some(authority))` — only the authorized wallet can move their player
- `require!(player.mass != 0)` — cannot interact if not in game
- `require!(map.key() == player.map)` — cannot interact with wrong map
- Collision detection is done inside `eat-player` system on-chain — no client verification

